        ],
        [
          "Clustering",
          "Higher Education",
          "Not Applicable",
          "662 students who have dropped out",
          "4 majors: Engineering, STEM, Law, Economics and Social Sciences, Linguistics and cultural Sciences",
          "Student Interviews. Data is divided into main categories:\n\n1. Interest/ Expectations\n\n2. Performance/ Requirements\n\n3. Financial Aspects\n\n4. Study Conditions\n\n5. Job Alternative/ Career\n\n6. Personal/ Family Aspects\n\n",
          "Vincent Tinto’s Model for Student Attrition",
          "[Drop Interest Field, Drop Expect, Drop Wish Practice, Drop No Practice, Drop Exam, Drop Require, Drop Material, drop Perform, Drop Activ, Drop Financial, Drop Moneymaking, Drop Anonym, Drop Overcrowd, Drop Orga, Drop Tuition, Drop Job, Drop Suitability, Drop Interest Job, Drop Opportunities, Drop Child, Drop Family, Drop Ill, Drop Pregnant, Drop Abroad]",
          "The NEPS dataset conducts interviews with their students and the authors use this dataset. While there is some worry with pre-processing such as identification of different types of Missing Value, authors use PCA on the feature set to reduce dimensionality. \n\n",
          "Hierarchical Clustering",
          "{Silhouette Score: 0.634 - 8 Clusters wih reduced Feature Set}",
          "8",
          "Clusters 1 and 2: The largest clusters with a mix of all reasons for dropout. Difference is that Cluster 2 has a big prevalence of Family Reasons while Cluster 1 doesn’t.\n\nClusters 3 and 4: These students reported a combined of 3 or 4 motives for dropout. Cluster 3 specific is mostly comprised of second and third year droouts who argued for study-related reasons.\n\nCluster 5: Students who reported interest, expectations and performance rrelated problems - mainly early dropouts.\n\nCluster 6: Cited study conditions along wqith family/personal motives for dropping out.\n\nCluster 7: Mostly lack of interest and unfulfilled expectations.\n\nCluster 8: Early dropouts who leave because of mainly personal or family reasons.",
          "Programmes may focus on addressing the most relevant reasons for student dropout: \n\n1. The gap in expectation vs reality.\n\n2. Take care of possibly unrealistic expectations on study requirements. \n\nBoth could be achieved by greater comunication between university and Highschools.\n\nMoreover, depending on program type, htere are differences in Dropout. Thus, the emasures that should be taken for distinct programs should probably be accounted for - STEM students foten leave for personal/financial reasons. ",
          "Authors look to cluster different motives for Dropout. \n\nAuthors do a series of discussions of motives for dropout according to different individual characteristics. Clustering is used afterward to cluster dropout motives using all predictors.",
          "Panel attrition and missing values on motive for dropout.\n\nSmall sample size, that could benefit from more instances.\n\nExclusive use of Hierarchical Clsutering without attempting other approaches.\n\nSubpar results on entire feature subset. Usage of PCA to bypass feature selection/Feature engineering. "
        ]
      ],
      "index": 4
    }
  ],
